summary: I can’t actually deal with sad drunk Crowley. The way he mocks his own choices leading to his fall, “Lucifer aND thE guuuuys”,...
body: I can’t actually deal with sad drunk Crowley. The way he mocks his own choices leading to his fall, “Lucifer aND thE guuuuys”, the way his voice breaks when he’s describing the actual fall. His soft incredulity when seeing Aziraphale. The way he sounds like he’s struggling not to sob while trying to tell Zira that all of his bookshop is gone, then elation because he still has what Zira needs!! and then returning to their old dynamic a bit when he repeats ‘I heard that - with a wiggle on’ (which sounds adorably snakey btw).

summary: The fact that his emotions affect how his eyes look makes it all the more plausible that he could start partially changing into...
question: The fact that his emotions affect how his eyes look makes it all the more plausible that he could start partially changing into snake form if he got upset enough.
answer:
And also his willpower, since when he drove through the M25′s fiery ring his eyes were fully golden as he used his imagination to make the Bentley invincible.

But yeah I definitely accept that headcanon of him going full snake-demon if someone pisses him off enough.

summary: I've been absorbed by the world of Good Omens
body:
I’ve been absorbed by the world of Good Omens

Uhhhh, I’m not good at this stuff. Am I even supposed to introduce myself or do I just appear? Anyways, hi, I’m Max and I fell in love with Good Omens when I saw the trailers. I had never heard of the book before but I had read another book by Neil Gaiman before–The Graveyard Book–which I loved. So yeah, I’m here to love on Crowley and Aziraphale and praise both Gaiman’s talent at writing novels and scripts.
